# University Elective Course Management System ERD – Explained

## Overview

This database is designed to manage a **University Elective Course Management System**, including academic structure, students, instructors, courses, semesters, sections, and enrollment records.

The system supports organizing university academic entities and managing student enrollment in elective and compulsory courses.

---

## Core Design Principles

- Normalized relational database design to reduce redundancy
- Clear separation of academic entities
- Shared `Person` entity for reusable personal information
- Primary and foreign key constraints for referential integrity
- Junction table design to resolve many-to-many relationships
- Scalable academic hierarchy

---

## Domain Summary

This system models the academic structure of a university and how students interact with course offerings.

Academic hierarchy:

**University → School → Department → Major → Student**

Operational workflow:

**Course → Section → Enrollment ← Student**

This structure supports academic management while keeping the schema organized and scalable.

---

## Entities

### University
Stores university-level information.

**Includes:**
- University ID
- University Name
- Website
- Address
- Established Year

**Relationship:**
- One university can have many schools (**1:M**)

---

### School
Represents academic schools or faculties.

**Includes:**
- School ID
- School Name
- University ID
- Dean Person ID

**Relationships:**
- Belongs to one university
- One school can have many departments (**1:M**)
- One school can have many instructors (**1:M**)

---

### Department
Represents academic departments within a school.

**Includes:**
- Department ID
- Department Name
- School ID

**Relationship:**
- One department can have many majors (**1:M**)

---

### Major
Represents academic programs or specializations.

**Includes:**
- Major ID
- Major Name
- Duration
- Department ID

**Relationship:**
- One major can have many students (**1:M**)

---

### Person
Stores shared personal information.

Used to avoid duplicated student/instructor data.

**Includes:**
- Person ID
- Full Name
- Birth Date
- Gender

**Used by:**
- Student
- Instructor
- School dean reference

---

### Student
Represents enrolled students.

**Includes:**
- Student ID
- Person ID
- Major ID
- Enrollment Year

**Relationship:**
- One student can have many enrollments (**1:M**)

---

### Instructor
Represents teaching staff.

**Includes:**
- Instructor ID
- Person ID
- School ID
- Title

**Relationship:**
- One instructor can teach many sections (**1:M**)

---

### Course
Represents course definitions.

**Includes:**
- Course ID
- Course Name
- Course Type
- Credits

**Business Rule:**
- Courses may be elective or compulsory

**Relationship:**
- One course can have many sections (**1:M**)

---

### Semester
Represents academic periods.

**Examples:**
- Fall 2025
- Spring 2026
- Summer 2026

**Includes:**
- Semester ID
- Semester Name
- Start Date
- End Date

**Relationship:**
- One semester can contain many sections (**1:M**)

---

### Section
Represents scheduled course offerings.

Separates course definition from actual delivery.

**Includes:**
- Section ID
- Section Name
- Class Number
- Class Location
- Class Time
- Enrollment Capacity
- Course ID
- Semester ID
- Instructor ID

**Relationships:**
- Belongs to one course
- Belongs to one semester
- Assigned to one instructor

---

### Enrollment
Represents student course registrations.

Acts as the junction table between students and sections.

**Includes:**
- Enrollment ID
- Student ID
- Section ID
- Enrollment Date
- Regular Grade
- Final Exam Grade
- Status

**Business Rules:**
- A student can enroll in multiple sections
- A section can contain multiple students
- Grades may remain NULL until assigned

---

## Relationship Summary

| Relationship | Type |
|------------|------|
| University → School | 1:M |
| School → Department | 1:M |
| School → Instructor | 1:M |
| Department → Major | 1:M |
| Major → Student | 1:M |
| Person → Student | 1:1 (logical inheritance) |
| Person → Instructor | 1:1 (logical inheritance) |
| Course → Section | 1:M |
| Semester → Section | 1:M |
| Instructor → Section | 1:M |
| Student ↔ Section | M:N (via Enrollment) |

---

## Design Decisions

### Shared Person Entity
The `Person` table stores common personal information used by both students and instructors, reducing redundancy.

---

### Enrollment as Junction Table
The `Enrollment` table resolves the many-to-many relationship between students and sections.

Without this design, student-course registration would be difficult to manage efficiently.

---

### Section-Based Course Delivery
The `Section` entity separates course definitions from scheduled offerings.

This allows:

- Database Systems → Fall 2025 Section A
- Database Systems → Spring 2026 Section B

---

### Academic Hierarchy
The schema follows a scalable academic structure:

```text
University
   └── School
         └── Department
               └── Major
                     └── Student

